Clearly not. The creature merely whistled and tried to charge straight at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite its size, it was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi couldn't help but scream when she nearly lost her grip on its too smooth scales.
"How do you kill them?" Nyssi screamed.
"GO FOR THEIR HEADS!"
"It's not going to be easy!"
Thassalin puffed out his breath and circled to approach the mountain he called home. The black beast followed, somewhat panicked when a bolt of fire struck it from behind. The creature hadn't noticed it was no longer alone. Its panic grew when Thassalin slowed, then struck it viciously with the tip of his tail, throwing it off course.
Groaning and whistling, the creature took to the air and spat upwards. Suddenly, everything turned black, as if the monster was sucking in the sky's light and replacing it with a perpetual cloud of night.
With no visibility left, Thassalin tried to retreat, but crashed into the treetops before landing in the clearing. As if it knew exactly where he had fallen, the creature charged straight at him, dragging the dark cloud in its wake.
"Tayel !", exclaimed Tenuk as he emerged from the cloud and began to circle in the air to try and spot Nyssi and Thassalin below in the darkness. "What do we do, Tayel ? Tayel... ? Tayel, where are you ?"
Below, Nyssi managed to get up as best she could. She was sure she must have broken something, but her strange healing powers, far from natural, had already started to take effect. Thassalin, on the other hand, lay on a mound, leaning against the only tree that hadn't bent under his weight. Nyssi did her best to try and reach Thassalin, but she couldn't see two meters in front of her. Everything was plunged into darkness, engulfed in unholy shadows. And in those shadows, something screamed.
A horrible whip-like tail came down beside Nyssi, knocking her over. However, she noticed that the tail was swaying, not aiming at her. The creature, as much as Nyssi could see and hear, growled and clawed at the shadows it had created. Something teleported through the darkness, striking the monster and disorienting it.
A sudden gunshot rang out, and the monster collapsed silently, motionless. The darkness surrounding them dissipated, revealing what had happened. Standing on top of the creature was Kayel, gun in hand and breathing heavily.
"It's... the strangest shadow leap I've ever done... Thanto kat'olon...", panted Kayel. His eyes shone with a black light, and a dark energy coursed through his body. However, as he spoke, Kayel's organic plating returned to its color, and his eyes regained their normal yellow hue.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They all knew that Kayel possessed strange shadow powers. He used them rarely, as most people considered them unholy and rather terrifying. But Nyssi didn't know that Kayel could use these powers in the dark. And, judging by his behavior, Kayel seemed surprised too.
"Are you okay?", Nyssi couldn't help asking.
"Yes, I'm fine. I killed something. It will feel better in a minute." Kayel examined his work, while Tenuk made his way to land beside him, reverting to his normal Spast form.
Now that the creature wasn't moving anymore, they could see better what it was. Its skin was black as coal and sticky, but the saliva continued to adhere to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, each ending in long claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what that thing was, something screamed and leaped from a nearby bush. However, the beast didn't have time to reach them, as a familiar vehicle crashed into its flank, sending it sprawling at Nyssi's feet. Not taking any chances, she grabbed her gun and immediately shot it in the head, killing the creature on the spot.
"Oh dear...", muttered Retvik from the driver's seat, before clumsily shutting off the engine and jumping down from the truck. "I, uh, didn't mean to do that. Are you okay?"
"You almost missed all the action," regretted Tenuk. "Where were you?"
"You abandoned me all along. I came here as fast as I could," sighed Retvik. "Can anyone tell me what these disgusting things are?"
Retvik's question received a response from Thassalin, who had just stood up. He was cut and scratched all over and seemed a bit disoriented, but he didn't appear to be too badly hurt.
"You KILLED THE CORRUPTIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES LEFT HERE WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean... the horrible god-monster that we... helped kill?"
"Yes. Absolutely. There might be others, but I didn't manage to aim for their heads. I'm missing a gun. Plus, two against one, that's not fair, isn't it?" Thassalin approached Kayel and patted his head. "Thanks, little one. You remind me of my old friend Arkadin, but less murderous and less capable of killing universes."
"Eh... thanks... I suppose," said Kayel shrugging. "So, we're done here?"
Nyssi shrugged, then took out her camera to photograph the now definitively dead beasts. She then pulled out her favorite dagger, the Death God's dagger, and began cutting one of the creature's horns, before moving to the other. But just as she finished, the creatures burst into flames and rapidly turned into piles of ashes. The same thing happened to the horns Nyssi had cut.
"Well... it's both convenient and not at all convenient," she sighed. "At least, I still have the photos..."
